entry.et: Middle English, from Old English ǣmettig unoccupied, from ǣmetta leisure, perhaps from ǣ- without + -metta (probably akin to mōtan to have to) must

def.dt: :containing nothing empty shelves
:not occupied or inhabited an empty building
:unfrequented
:not pregnant empty heifer
:null 4a the empty set
:lacking reality, substance, meaning, or value :hollow an empty pleasure
:destitute of effect or force an empty threat
:devoid of sense :foolish
:hungry
:idle empty hours
:having no purpose or result :useless
:marked by the absence of human life, activity, or comfort an empty silence

entry.pt: empty vacant blank void vacuous mean lacking contents which could or should be present. empty suggests a complete absence of contents an empty bucket. vacant suggests an absence of appropriate contents or occupants a vacant apartment. blank stresses the absence of any significant, relieving, or intelligible features on a surface a blank wall. void suggests absolute emptiness as far as the mind or senses can determine a statement void of meaning. vacuous suggests the emptiness of a vacuum and especially the lack of intelligence or significance a vacuous facial expression.

:deprive divest a phrase emptied of all meaning
:to discharge (itself) of contents
:to fire (a repeating firearm) until empty

:calories from food that supplies energy but is not nutritionally balanced
:having or bringing nothing
